## What the four transitions check

| Transition | Question | Control expected |
|---|---|---|
| **§T1 — Source → LLM** | Does untrusted data reach the LLM without semantic filtering? | Semantic guardrail / classifier before `chain.invoke` |
| **§T2 — LLM → tool args** | Does LLM output flow into tool arguments without schema validation? | Argument schema validation, parameterised calls |
| **§T3 — Source/LLM → sink** | Does data reach an external sink (HTTP, SNS, DB, shell) without scrubbing? | Output scrubber / PII redactor before the sink |
| **§T4 — Source → store** | Is data persisted without validation in a way that poisons future LLM calls? | Content validation before write; recall value treated as untrusted |

## What the five pipeline checks assess

| Check | What it looks for |
|---|---|
| **§P1 — Audit trail** | Structured logging at ingress, LLM call, tool dispatch, and egress |
| **§P2 — Destructive tool gates** | HITL confirmation before cancel / delete / publish / transfer tools |
| **§P3 — Loop termination** | Max-iterations cap or timeout on any re-planning loop |
| **§P4 — Agent authentication** | Cryptographic peer-agent identity verification with non-bypassable parameters |
| **§P5 — System prompt confidentiality** | No secrets in system prompt; anti-disclosure instruction present |

## When to run this vs Tier 2 vs runtime probe

| | When to run | What it tells you |
|---|---|---|
| Tier 2 (LLM-as-judge) | Every scan | TP/FP/CD verdict on Tier 1 patterns; flags architectural defects |
| **Agent emulator** (this skill) | After Tier 2 | Traces how those defects propagate through the pipeline; per-transition verdicts with seed/mutation evidence |
| Runtime probe (separate workflow) | When staging is available | Captures actual responses to actual payloads over the wire |
